ce:section.ce:para:
The schematic model of the activation of the MoS2 basal plane by CQDs was shown to describe the pathway of hydrogen spillover (Fig. 1a
                        ). The design was caused by the strong proton adsorption capacity of CQDs, which could compensate for the weak adsorption of protons on the surface of MoS2-based catalysts. The CQDs with abundant functional groups readily interacts strongly with MoS2 through surface functional groups to influence surface structure and charge distribution of MoS2@CQDs catalysts. The carbon clusters were constructed with various numbers of carbon atoms to estimate the proton adsorption energy of CQDs by the DFT calculations. The values of Ea were defined to determine a possible proton collection in the sites of CQDs. The values of calculated CQDs models with one proton were less than −4.75 eV (Fig. 1b and c), demonstrating a strong adsorption. The C6 cluster was selected to estimate the adsorption of different numbers of protons for subsequent optimization calculations. The negative value of Ea indicated how many protons the carbon cluster could hold (Fig. 1d), suggesting that the C6 cluster could interact with up 8 protons. This was mainly due to the interaction between C–O–Mo bonds to promote the hydrogen spillover effect of MoS2@CQDs (Fig. S1a). The strength of this effect can be represented by the surface charge distribution and electronic structure. The surface charge distribution can be imaged by differential charge density and charge density distribution. The purple means electron-enriched areas, while the orange means electron-deficient areas in differential charge density (Fig. 2
                        a). The cross-distribution of electron gain and loss can be observed at the domain around CQDs and S atoms on MoS2 surface, indicating an optimized surface activity of MoS2. The two-dimensional (2D) charge density distribution showed the electron-rich CQDs end and other electron-deficient sites over the model (Fig. 2b, S1b). The electron-rich CQDs end would be beneficial to the H* adsorption. Simultaneously, the electron-deficient sites would have the weak adsorption. The charge density demonstrated a weakened gradient from C at CQDs end to S atom on MoS2 surface. The changing trend can illustrate the weakened hydrogen adsorption. The successively weakened adsorption could form an effective hydrogen spillover pathway for quick H* transport. The Bader charge analysis was used to quantify the number of transfer electrons (Fig. S1c). The transfer electrons from carbon atom of CQDs to oxygen atom on MoS2 surface around ∼0.42 e, regulating the activity of basal plane. The ELF mapping was used to reflect the bond strength between MoS2 and CQDs (Fig. 2c). The electron localized area was “petal-like” at the center of oxygen atoms. The direction of petals was toward C and Mo atoms to form a stable C–O–Mo bond. Notably, the unpaired electrons on CQDs end can easily interact with protons, facilitating proton collection on the surface of MoS2@CQDs (Fig. 2d). The electronic structure reorganization was analyzed by the local DOS (LDOS) and project DOS (PDOS). The increased electron states around the Fermi level (EF) appeared to enhance electronic conductivity (Fig. 2e, S1d), which boosted electron transfer during catalytic reaction. The synchronous peaks occurring in PDOS plots of C 2p, O 2p and Mo 3d orbitals near the EF indicated that the stable C–O–Mo bond could form via orbital hybridization (Fig. 2f).
